Theorem 2: The Dummy Tax (Monotonic Relaxation)
When to use it: You are sweeping a window, and expanding the window adds a penalty (like distance or rent). 
You are using a Priority Queue to manage the items inside the window.

The Law: If the penalty to expand the window strictly increases (e.g., moving j to the right makes (b_j - b_i) larger), 
you do not need to protect your boundary elements.
The Proof of Safety:
The Overcharge: If your queue pops the boundary element a_j, your code will calculate a "wrong", overpriced penalty for the remaining elements.
The Eviction: This overpriced penalty might cause your queue to panic and pop other good elements.

The Guarantee: If a good element is destroyed by the "wrong" penalty at step j, it is dead anyway! 
Because the penalty strictly increases, it mathematically could never survive step j+1, j+2, or $j+3$.

The Strategy: Push everything, including boundaries, into the queue. Let the queue pop whatever it wants. 
You will calculate "wrong" intermediate states, but you will never miss the optimal answer because the exact, perfect boundaries will be naturally tested by your for loops.
